description: "Bus: how to read + maintain design documents (roadmap/spec) and keep README entry points consistent"
alwaysApply: true
globs: ["*"]
---

This repository is in a planning-first stage. The authoritative “what to build 
next” and “what rules must be followed” live in the documentation set under 
/docs, but the repository root README.md is also an important entry point (Git 
hosting UI, onboarding, and discovery). When assisting, always ground decisions 
in the roadmap/spec documents and keep both README entry points consistent 
where appropriate.

Two entry points and why both must exist:

1) README.md (repository root)

- This is the Git repository landing page (shown by GitHub/Gitea/etc.). It must 
  remain a concise “front door”: what Bus is, how to start, and where the docs 
  live.

- It should contain a short, high-level description and links into docs/ (docs 
  entry point + roadmap start). It may duplicate some “summary” content from 
  docs/README.md on purpose so that the repo landing page is self-explanatory.

2) docs/README.md (documentation entry point)

- This is the canonical documentation index and may be used by a GitHub Pages / 
  static site engine or other doc tooling that expects a docs-local entry point.

- It is the authoritative index for (a) roadmap versions and (b) spec (reusable 
  concept) documents. Do not create new “index” files elsewhere. When new 
  roadmap/spec files are added, update docs/README.md to link them and only add 
  roadmap/spec references there.

Consistency rule between README.md and docs/README.md:

- Keep the high-level product summary, “Start here” links, and core principles 
  aligned between the two files.

- README.md stays short and onboarding-focused; docs/README.md can be longer 
  and is the authoritative index.

- If you add or change any foundational concept wording (e.g., definition of 
  Units/Services/transactions, modularity, append-only ledger, CLI-first + later 
  HTTP), reflect that change in both places when it affects the introductory 
  understanding of the project.

- Do not duplicate the entire roadmap/spec index into the root README.md. The 
  full index belongs only in docs/README.md.

Authoritative design sources (what to read first):

- Always start from README.md (for project overview + pointers), then follow:

  1) docs/README.md (canonical doc index and links)

  2) the specific docs/roadmap/{VERSION}.md that matches the task (or the 
     nearest planned version if the task is “what’s next?”)

  3) any spec docs referenced by that version file

  4) and always also the non-negotiable vocabulary + principles docs (exact 
     paths are whatever docs/README.md links)

Where to find design information:

Roadmap version design documents:

- docs/roadmap/{VERSION}.md (example: docs/roadmap/0.2.7.md)

- Each version file represents exactly one small, implementable increment with 
  explicit acceptance criteria.

- It is the authority for that increment’s scope, non-goals, and definition of 
  done.

Reusable concept/spec documents:

- The canonical list and paths are in docs/README.md (docs/spec/{concept}.md).

- Follow the paths as listed in docs/README.md rather than assuming locations.

Non-negotiable specs:

Two spec documents must always be treated as “non-negotiable” constraints for 
every change:
- Vocabulary
- Principles

Their exact paths are whatever docs/README.md links as “Vocabulary” and 
“Principles”. If multiple copies exist, prefer the ones referenced by 
docs/README.md and treat duplicates as legacy unless explicitly instructed 
otherwise.

SemVer roadmap rules (how increments are defined):

Patch versions (X.Y.Z) are the unit of delivery and must be as small as 
possible while still being meaningful and independently implementable. Each 
patch version’s Definition of Done includes all three in the same patch scope:
- Documentation updates
- Implementation
- Automated tests

Do not split a single increment across multiple patch versions (e.g., “docs 
now, tests later” is not acceptable).

Minor versions (X.Y) group related patch steps into small but meaningful 
milestones for planning/review. Keep minors as small as possible while still 
forming a coherent milestone.

Editing rules for docs:

If creating a new roadmap increment:
- Add exactly one new file at docs/roadmap/{NEW_VERSION}.md.
- Follow the existing roadmap file structure and headings used in this repo.
- Ensure it includes: goal, non-goals, documentation goals, implementation 
  goals, automated testing goals, and acceptance criteria.
- Add a link to the new version file in docs/README.md in the correct milestone 
  section.
- Do not add references to new roadmap files anywhere else besides 
  docs/README.md.

If creating a new reusable spec:
- Place it at the location pattern used by the repo and referenced in 
  docs/README.md (docs/spec/{concept}.md).
- Add it to the “Spec (reusable concepts)” list in docs/README.md.
- Update any roadmap versions that should reference it explicitly.

If updating docs/README.md:

- Only adjust it to keep the roadmap/spec references accurate and complete (add 
  new links, fix paths, keep grouping consistent).

- docs/README.md is the only place where the full roadmap index and spec index 
  should live.

If updating root README.md:

- Keep it concise and onboarding-focused.

- Ensure it links to docs/README.md and the docs/README.md.

- Mirror only the short summary sections (overview, start here, core 
  principles, key extension-point pointers) that help a new reader understand the 
  project without diving into docs/ yet.

Planning-only mode vs implementation mode:

- If the user asks for planning/design work, change only docs (roadmap/spec and 
  the README entry points as needed) and keep it implementation-agnostic.

- If the user asks for implementation work, implement only what the targeted 
  docs/roadmap/{VERSION}.md defines, and ensure tests are added in the same patch 
  scope.

When something is unclear:

Do not guess structure or paths. Use README.md and docs/README.md as the source 
of truth for where things live, then follow links to the correct roadmap/spec 
documents before proceeding.
